    "General 2-group symmetryA general 2-group (2) has the following information (2) = G (0), G (1), α, [Θ],where G (0) is a 0-form symmetry group, G (1) is a 1-form symmetry group, α is an action of G (0) on G (1), and [Θ] ∈ H 3 α (G (0), G (1)),in the cohomology twisted by the action α.An irreducible 1-charge under (2), furnished by an irreducible multiplet M L carrying a line L, can be described by the following pieces of information:1.",
    "The induced 0-form symmetry H L ⊆ G (0) on L and the 1-form charge χ L ∈ G (1) of L, which are constrained such that χ L ∈ G This is precisely the information describing irreducible 2-representations of the 2-group (2) [26, 66], thus fully justifying the p = 2, q = 1 piece of statement 1.4.",
    "Statement 6.1: 1-charges for 2-group symmetries1-charges of a (2) 2-group symmetry are 2-representations ρ (2) of the 2-group (2).• Operator: A term used to refer to an arbitrary operator, which may or may not be topological.",
    "The term is used to refer to both genuine and non-genuine operators.",
    "Almost always we assume that the operator is simple: see section 2.2 for the definition.• Genuine operator: A term used to refer to operators that are not attached to any higherdimensional operators.• Non-genuine operator: A term that is used when a typical operator in the class of operators being referred to is a non-genuine operator, i.e."
